sols_latex:
Differentiate both sides of $\displaystyle \tan y =x$ with respect to
$\displaystyle x$. (Don't forget to apply the chain rule!)

\begin{align*}
\frac{d}{dx} \tan y &= \frac{d}{dx} x \\ 
\sec^2 y \cdot \frac{dy}{dx} &=1 \\
\frac{dy}{dx} &= \frac{1}{\sec^2 y}.
\end{align*}

Now apply the trig identity $\sec^2 y =1 + \tan^2 y$ to get

\begin{align*}
\frac{dy}{dx} = \frac{1}{1+\tan^2y} = {\color{blue} \frac{1}{1+x^2}}
\end{align*}

after noting that $\displaystyle \tan y =x \implies \tan^2 y = x^2$.

